Related Resources

     * [http://www.gnu.org/software/gsl/]GSL (GNU Scientific Library) brew
       install gsl
     * [https://opencv.org/]OpenCV brew tap homebrew/science && brew
       install opencv
     * [http://www.graphviz.org/]Graphviz brew install graphviz
     * [http://www.gnuplot.info/]Gnuplot brew install gnuplot --with-x11
     * [https://www.xquartz.org/]X11/XQuartz
     * [https://www.imagemagick.org/script/index.php]ImageMagick &&
       libjpeg brew install imagemagick && brew install libjpeg
     * [http://www.r-project.org/]R brew tap homebrew/science && brew
       install r
     * [https://www.gnu.org/software/octave/]Octave brew tap
       homebrew/science && brew install octave --without-docs
     * [http://scikit-learn.org/stable/tutorial/machine_learning_map/]scik
       it-learn algorithm cheatsheet
     * [https://github.com/markets/awesome-ruby#natural-language-processin
       g]Awesome Ruby - Among other awesome items a short list of NLP
       related projects.
     * [https://github.com/diasks2/ruby-nlp]Ruby NLP - State-of-Art
       collection of Ruby libraries for NLP.
     * [https://github.com/edobashira/speech-language-processing]Speech
       and Natural Language Processing - General List of NLP related
       resources (mostly not for Ruby programmers).
     * [http://sciruby.com/]Scientific Ruby - Linear Algebra,
       Visualization and Scientific Computing for Ruby.
     * [https://github.com/SciRuby/iruby]iRuby - IRuby kernel for Jupyter
       (formelly IPython).
     * [https://github.com/thbar/kiba]Kiba - Lightweight
       [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extract,_transform,_load]ETL
       (Extract, Transform, Load) pipeline.
     * [https://github.com/kba/awesome-ocr]Awesome OCR - Multitude of OCR
       (Optical Character Recognition) resources.
     * [https://github.com/jtoy/awesome-tensorflow]Awesome TensorFlow -
       Machine Learning with TensorFlow libraries.
     * [https://github.com/SciRuby/rb-gsl]rb-gsl - Ruby interface to the
       [https://www.gnu.org/software/gsl/]GNU Scientific Library.
     * [https://silverhammermba.github.io/emberb/]The Definitive Guide to
       Ruby's C API - Modern Reference and Tutorial on Embedding and
       Extending Ruby using C programming language.

Wait but why?

   There are a lot of software lists with ML related tools. There are a
   couple of lists with Ruby related projects. There are no lists of only
   working and tested software with documented scope. We'll try to make
   one!

   What is awesome? Awesome are documented, maintained and focused tools.

   Can something turn not awesome at a point? Yes! Abandoned projects with
   broken dependencies aren't awesome any more! They leave this list.

